[
  {
    "content_id": 20000,
    "reference_id": 19168,
    "title": "Lamentations 1:1–22",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25001001-25001022",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>Chapter 1 mourns the destruction and desolation of Jerusalem, recognizing that this was God’s well-deserved judgment on Israel’s sins.</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25001001",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:1",
          "end_ref": "25001022",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:22"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20008,
    "reference_id": 19176,
    "title": "Lamentations 1:2",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25001002",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>The lovers were the fertility deities, Baal and Asherah, who were worshiped by most people in Judah. Her friends were her military allies, notably Egypt, who was no match for Babylon (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer37:5-Jer37:11\">Jer 37:5–11</a>).</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25001002",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:2",
          "end_ref": "25001002",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:2"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20009,
    "reference_id": 19177,
    "title": "Lamentations 1:3",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25001003",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>The woman of <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lam1:1\">1:1</a> is the nation of Judah. •&nbsp;led away into captivity: This happened four times: 605&nbsp;BC (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan1:3-Dan1:4\">Dan 1:3–4</a>); 597&nbsp;BC (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs24:12-2Kgs24:16\">2&nbsp;Kgs 24:12–16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:28\">Jer 52:28</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek1:2-Ezek1:3\">Ezek 1:2–3</a>); 586&nbsp;BC (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs25:5-2Kgs25:7\">2&nbsp;Kgs 25:5–7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs25:18-2Kgs25:21\">18–21</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer39:5-Jer39:10\">Jer 39:5–10</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:29\">52:29</a>); and 581&nbsp;BC (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:30\">Jer 52:30</a>).</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25001003",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:3",
          "end_ref": "25001003",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:3"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20010,
    "reference_id": 19178,
    "title": "Lamentations 1:4",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25001004",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>Jerusalem (Hebrew <em>Zion</em>): In the Psalms and in the prophetic books, Zion represents the city of Jerusalem. In Lamentations, Zion is a poetic name for the city, even in ruins. <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb12:22-Heb12:24\">Hebrews 12:22–24</a> speaks of the heavenly Zion (see also <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:1-Rev14:5\">Rev 14:1–5</a>). •&nbsp;The annual festivals in Jerusalem were the Passover, Unleavened Bread, First Harvest, Harvest (Pentecost), Trumpets, the Day of Atonement, and Shelters (Tabernacles). •&nbsp;The main duties of the priests were carried out in the Temple and its surrounding area. Since the Temple was in ruins, they had no jobs and hence no future.</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25001004",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:4",
          "end_ref": "25001004",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:4"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20011,
    "reference_id": 19179,
    "title": "Lamentations 1:5",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25001005",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>for her many sins: Judah’s sins before the Babylonian invasion are outlined in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs21:1-2Kgs21:9\">2&nbsp;Kgs 21:1–9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs21:16\">16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs24:3-2Kgs24:4\">24:3–4</a> (cp. <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr33:1-2Chr33:10\">2&nbsp;Chr 33:1–10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr33:22-2Chr33:23\">22–23</a> and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr36:11-2Chr36:16\">2&nbsp;Chr 36:11–16</a>). Similarly, a list of Israel’s sins before Assyria destroyed it is found in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs17:14-2Kgs17:23\">2&nbsp;Kgs 17:14–23</a>.</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25001005",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:5",
          "end_ref": "25001005",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 1:5"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
