    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20023,
    "reference_id": 19191,
    "title": "Lamentations 2:3–4",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25002003-25002004",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>bends his bow: In the past, the Lord had been a mighty warrior on Israel’s behalf (see <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod14:13-Exod15:21\">Exod 14:13–15:21</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh23:9-Josh23:11\">Josh 23:9–11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg7:1-Judg7:25\">Judg 7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs19:32-2Kgs19:35\">2&nbsp;Kgs 19:32–35</a>); now he waged war against Jerusalem (see <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa63:10\">Isa 63:10</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek24:25\">Ezek 24:25</a>).</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25002003",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:3",
          "end_ref": "25002004",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:4"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20024,
    "reference_id": 19192,
    "title": "Lamentations 2:6",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25002006",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>A garden shelter was a temporary structure that harvesters put up to provide shade. God had promised to take care of his Temple forever (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs9:3\">1&nbsp;Kgs 9:3</a>), but now it seemed that he had abandoned it.</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25002006",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:6",
          "end_ref": "25002006",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:6"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20025,
    "reference_id": 19193,
    "title": "Lamentations 2:7",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25002007",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>The Temple was destroyed because the sins that the priests and the people had committed within its walls had defiled its holiness (cp. <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer7:3-Jer7:15\">Jer 7:3–15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer26:3-Jer26:6\">26:3–6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer26:12-Jer26:13\">12–13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek24:21\">Ezek 24:21</a>).</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25002007",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:7",
          "end_ref": "25002007",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:7"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20026,
    "reference_id": 19194,
    "title": "Lamentations 2:8",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25002008",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>Ramparts were stone walls or mounds of earth built around a city to protect it from assault by an enemy army.</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25002008",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:8",
          "end_ref": "25002008",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:8"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20027,
    "reference_id": 19195,
    "title": "Lamentations 2:9",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25002009",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>no more visions: Daniel and Ezekiel were prophets of the Lord who had visions while they lived among the exiles far from the land of Judah (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek1:1\">Ezek 1:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan7:1\">Dan 7:1</a>). This verse refers to prophets in Jerusalem who claimed to have visions that proved to be false.</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25002009",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:9",
          "end_ref": "25002009",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:9"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
    "content_id": 20015,
    "reference_id": 19183,
    "title": "Lamentations 2:10",
    "media_type": "Text",
    "index_reference": "25002010",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<p>Burlap (or <em>sackcloth</em>) was made of goat or camel hair and was often used for grain sacks or for items to be carried on pack animals. Poor people wore it as clothing because it was inexpensive, and people in mourning wore it as a sign of&nbsp;their deep&nbsp;sorrow (its dark color matched their mood, and its roughness matched their discomfort). •&nbsp;Throwing dust on their heads and clothing was a sign to neighbors that a family member had died.</p>",
    "associations": {
      "passage": [
        {
          "start_ref": "25002010",
          "start_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:10",
          "end_ref": "25002010",
          "end_ref_usfm": "LAM 2:10"
        }
      ],
      "resource": []
    }
  },
  {
